	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">noattack wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It seems most people sputter out after realizing how tough it is to program for the NES.  I've been reading off and on for over a year now and I still feel like a beginner.  Everyone learns at different speeds, so stick with it and you'll do fine.  You just have to really love the NES to get past the learning curve.</div>
<br />
<br />Very true! I'd like to point out that once you understand how to get things to run on the NES, it's not really a case of it being hard. The difficult part is trying to learn how to code <em>well</em> for efficiency. This is something that I struggle with, but I feel like I get new revelations on how to do things with each new program I make. This is why I like to recommend to people that they should start small. In this way, they don't get in over their head, and at the same time get some satisfaction out of a finished product.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
